In 368— PH. Tu me vidisti? Sc. Atque his quidem hercle oculis.

PH. Carebis credo.

Birt would read corgo (explained by Paul. Fest. as=profecto). But this semi-ironical use of words like credo, opinor, “ I am thinking‚” is quite Plautine z cp. Cas. 111. 6. ε), dabo tibi μέγα κακόν ut opinor. He would introduce the same word, or in some cases probe ego instead of projecto, wherever it occurs, and often instead of hercle and other exclamations‚ when the metre would be improved by the change.
